data.title: Photos:: 50 most beautiful female celebrities
data.text:
Where you’ve seen her: She was Dr. Remy Hadley on the eight-season TV show “House,” but you probably know her as Thirteen Why we love her: She’s a pretty face on television, but she’s also known for her charity work with Artists for Peace and Justice, Doctors Without Borders and her PBS documentary series called “Half the Sky.” (Al Seib / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: She played Brad Pitt’s mother in “The Curious Case of Benjamin Button,” Tyrese’s wacky love interest in “Baby Boy” and the independent woman in “Think Like a Man” Why we love her: She’s beautiful but her talent has earned many awards and award nominations for an Oscar and Emmy, too. (Kirk McKoy / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On the big screen as a good vamp in the Twilight series Why we love her: She’s the bubbly, optimistic vamp in the Twilight series -- which is a nice change from the angst-fest we get from the rest of the fanged ones! (Jay L. Clendenin / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: Fans of the Bill Cosby spinoff show will remember her as Lena James on “A Different World,” but she’s also known for the voice of Gloria on “Madagascar,” Niobe on “The Matrix Revolution” and her TV show “Hawthorne” Why we love her: She’s married to rapper/actor Will Smith but has a love for rock with her band Wicked Wisdom. She can act, dance and is the free-spirited mother of child actors Willow and Jaden Smith. (Kirk McKoy / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On her reality shows “Keeping Up With the Kardashians” and “Kim and Kourtney Take Miami,” and at every red carpet known to man Why we love her: She’s a woman who knows what she wants (endless attention), and knows how to get it. She’s also rapper Kanye West’s better half. (Gina Ferazzi / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: You may remember her as the kid actor starring alongside Samuel L. Jackson in “Eve’s Bayou” or her later work in “Think Like a Man,” “Waist Deep” and TV show “Deception” Why we love her: She’s clearly drinking from the fountain of youth and can easily play the college girlfriend in movies like “Stomp the Yard” and turn around and hop stairs and fight as an undercover cop. She’s also giving the thumbs up for abstinence before marriage, which she did until she married her husband DeVon Franklin. (Carolyn Cole / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: She kissed a girl, liked it and she sang about it Why we love her: The cheeky singer and songwriter knows how to make a splash, both with her music and on the red carpet. (Jay L. Clendenin / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On the big screen in “Slumdog Millionaire” Why we love her: Pinto burst onto the scene with “Slumdog Millionaire,” her first feature film. People magazine placed her on their “Most Beautiful People List” and “List of the World’s best Dressed Women.” We couldn’t agree more. (Dimitrios Kambouris / Getty Images)

Where you’ve seen her: She was in the underrated film “Losers,” but she’s clearly no loser. You may know her from the bridge of the starship Enterprise in the new “Star Trek” reboot. Why we love her: She’s Lt. Uhura 2.0! We’re geek enough to find that unbearably hot. (Al Seib / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: Don’t pronounce Ling with a hard “L” on “Ally McBeal” or she will give you the stink eye. Or, maybe you recognize her as Dr. Joan Watson on “Elementary,” Viper on “Kung Fu Panda” and Officer Jessica Tang on “Southland” Why we love her: She always makes being a rebel sexy. (Jay L. Clendenin / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On screens both big and small ranging from “Think Like a Man,” Tyler Perry’s “Daddy’s Little Girls” and “Bring It On” Why we love her: We’ve adored Gabrielle since “Bring It On,” but our respect for her skyrocketed when she testified to the Senate Judiciary Committee, sharing her own horrific story of rape, in support of the Violence Against Women Act. She’s also the better half of Miami Heat basketball player Dwyane Wade. (Brian van der Brug / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On the arm of President Barack H. Obama and in just about every fashion magazine and blog there is Why we love her: We haven’t seen this much fashion sense since Jackie Kennedy Onassis. FLOTUS has not only been a fashion icon but she’s the brains behind the Let’s Move campaign to fight childhood obesity. (Michael Loccisano / Getty Images)

Where you know her from: Every single radio ever Why we love her: She’s cute as a button and she weathered many a storm this year. Some girls grow resentful of the ex-boyfriend but Taylor gets rich off of breakups. (Wally Skalij / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: You’ve heard one of her many Grammy-winning hits on the radio. She’s also the wife of hip-hop producer Swizz Beatz. Why we love her: For all those hits, for piano playing, and most of all, for Keep a Child Alive -- a charity she co-founded that provides medicines to families with HIV and AIDS in Africa. (Gina Ferazzi / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On the big screen Why we love her: She kicked butt in “Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon,” enchanted in “Memoirs of a Geisha,” showed off her tap-dancing skills (no, really!) in “Princess Raccoon,” and was the youngest person ever to sit on the jury of the Cannes Film Festival. Plus, she survived “Rush Hour 2” with her dignity intact! (STR / AFP/Getty Images)

Why you know her: She stole the hearts of both Ryan Gosling and Owen Wilson in “The Notebook” and “Wedding Crashers,” respectively. Why we love her: Have you seen her smile? It’s dazzling. We can’t wait to see her got toe-to-toe with Robert Downey Jr. in “Sherlock Holmes.” (Carolyn Cole / Los Angeles Times)

Where you know her from: The competitive arenas of wrestling and dance

Why we love her: It takes guts to leap into the wrestling ring — and then leap onto the dance floor of “Dancing with the Stars.” Plus, there are her nicknames: “The legs of the WWE” and “The Weapon of Mass Seduction” (Michael Buckner / Getty Images for ELLE)

Where you’ve seen her: On runways, in magazines and hosting “Project Runway”

Why we love her: Klum has been stalking the catwalk since 1992, but she’s hardly just a pretty face (and smokin’ bod). She won a Peabody award for Project Runway, for which she is host and executive producer. That’s the first Peabody award to a reality show. (Jay L. Clendenin / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On the silver screen, including an Oscar-winning turn in “Vicky Cristina Barcelona” and Anna in “To Rome With Love”

Why we love her: Have you seen Vicky Cristina Barcelona? How about all her roles in Pedro Almodóvar’s films? How can you not love a woman with that sort of talent? (Wally Skalij / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: On “That 70s Show,” “Forgetting Sarah Marshall” and as the funny but heart-on-her-sleeve love interest in “Friends With Benefits”

Why we love her: Yes, she’s cute as a button. Yes, she’s super talented. But we really love her the most because 1) she’s the voice of Meg in “Family Guy,” and Family guy equals instant adoration, and 2) she’s admitted she’s a huge fan of “World of Warcraft.” (Jay L. Clendenin / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: She’s been on countless runways, was a Victoria’s Secret model and is the producer of “America’s Next Top Model”

Why we love her: She knows all things fierce. She’s tapped into every form of entertainment there is, from acting (“Higher Learning” and “Love & Basketball”), charity work (TZONE Foundation) to singing and modeling. (Dimitrios Kambouris / Getty Images)

Why we love her: She’s a gorgeous woman who refuses to fix what others may see as flaws — “I have the hugest overbite. It’s so big, my older brothers and sisters used to call me “Bugs.” I looked like a bottle opener. But I’ve never fixed my bite because it’s one of the things that makes me me...My best feature is my big hips. I’ve got some nice childbearing hips, and I feel very proud of them. When I was younger I thought they were too big. I wanted to be slimmer. But now I totally embrace them.” (Kirk McKoy / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: She’s an Academy-Award-winning actress.

Why we love her: Her Oscar-winning performance in “Monster” was called “one of the greatest performances in the history of the cinema” by critic Roger Ebert. Plus she’s passionately committed to helping the people of her native South Africa -- her foundation provides health services for some of the poorest regions of the country. (Al Seib / Los Angeles Times)

Where you’ve seen her: You either laugh, cheer her on or both while watching her as Mrs. Smith on “Mr.and Mrs. Smith”

Why we love her: As much as she loves kids, we should love her for that alone. She’s the right-hand woman of actor Brad Pitt, but she is a business woman and philanthropist all her own. Outside of acting, her charity work includes UNICEF, ONE Campaign and UNHCR. (Al Seib / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: She’s the go-to geek-bait hot babe, and has appeared on countless magazine covers

Why we love her: This quote from The Times of London, when the reporter asked her if she considered herself a role model: “It depends on what your idea of a role model is. If your idea of a role model is somebody who’s gonna preach to your kids that sex before marriage is wrong and cursing is wrong and women should be this and be that, then I’m not a role model. But if you want your girls to feel strong and intelligent and be outspoken and fight for what they think is right, then I want to be that type of role model, yeah.” (Al Seib / Los Angeles Times)

Why you know her: She broke big with Lost in Translation and hasn’t slowed down since.

Why we love her: She’s a star who doesn’t starve herself, doesn’t advertise her personal business, and stays out of the tabloids. Plus, she’s about to kick Iron Man’s butt as the Black Widow! (Carolyn Cole / Los Angeles Times)

Where you know her from: Music, movies, awards shows.... where haven’t you seen her? She’s a new mom of her daughter Blue Ivy and the wife of rap star Jay-Z. She was also given the title as People’s 2012 World’s Most Beautiful Woman.

Why we love her: So many reasons, but mostly because “Single Ladies” is a song we’re almost glad will be stuck in our heads for the rest of our lives. She’s also no stranger to charity work, with Survivor Foundation being the most well-known for her contribution to Hurricane Katrina victims. (Jay L. Clendenin / Los Angeles Times)
